

# Research Agenda: Short-Skew / Vanna Strategy Optimizer

## 0. Working Notation

Let

$$
w_t^0 := w_{t-1}^{+}
$$

be yesterday’s position mapped into today’s live universe.

Define the trade vector:

$$
\Delta w_t := w_t - w_t^0
$$

Let

$$
B_t
$$

be the factor / Greek loading matrix.

Important exposure vectors:

$$
b_{\Gamma,t}, \quad b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}, \quad b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
$$

Factor exposure:

$$
x_t = B_t^\top w_t
$$

Trade-induced exposure change:

$$
\Delta x_t = B_t^\top \Delta w_t
$$

Transaction cost:

$$
C_t(w_t, w_t^0) = \sum_i c_{i,t} \lvert w_{i,t} - w_{i,t}^0 \rvert
$$

---

# Part I. Optimization Problem Reconstruction

## 1. Rethink the Construction of the Optimization Problem

The current optimizer may be solving the wrong problem.

The real problem is not:

$$
{}\text{find the best option basket every day}
$$

The real problem is closer to:

$$
{}\text{maintain a tradable Gamma/Vega-neutral, positive-Vanna structure at low cost}
$$

So the optimizer should be designed around path stability, not only one-period MVO.

---

## 2. Reconstruct the Optimization

Rewrite the optimizer around the current state:

$$
w_t^0 = w_{t-1}^{+}
$$

Instead of solving a fresh static problem every day, solve a state-dependent problem:

$$
\max_{w_t} \quad U_t(w_t) - U_t(w_t^0) - \kappa C_t(w_t, w_t^0)
$$

where

$$
U_t(w)
$$

is the estimated utility of holding portfolio $w$.

A simple version:

$$
U_t(w) = \mu_t^\top w - \frac{\gamma}{2} w^\top \Sigma_t w
$$

The optimizer should only trade if the utility improvement is large enough relative to cost.

---

## 3. Soft Tracking for Factor Exposure

Instead of forcing exact factor exposure targets, use soft tracking or bands.

For Gamma and Vega:

$$
\lvert b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\Gamma}
$$

$$
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}}
$$

Alternative soft-penalty form:

$$
\rho_{\Gamma}\left(b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w_t\right)^2
+
\rho_{\mathrm{Vega}}\left(b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t\right)^2
$$

For Vanna, do not force a fixed target. Use a wide feasible range:

$$
L_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
\le
b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}^\top w_t
\le
U_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
$$

---

## 4. Turnover Cost vs. Estimated Return

A key question:

$$
{}\text{Is the estimated alpha large enough to justify the turnover?}
$$

Compare expected alpha gain:

$$
\mu_t^\top \Delta w_t
$$

against transaction cost:

$$
\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert
$$

A useful diagnostic ratio:

$$
\frac{\mu_t^\top \Delta w_t}{\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert}
$$

If this ratio is often below 1, the optimizer is trading too much relative to its expected edge.

---

## 5. No-Trade Region

Introduce a no-trade region.

Current turnover penalty:

$$
\lambda_{\mathrm{tc}} \sum_i c_{i,t} \lvert w_{i,t} - w_{i,t}^0 \rvert
$$

Alternative no-trade constraint:

$$
\sum_i c_{i,t} \lvert w_{i,t} - w_{i,t}^0 \rvert \le \theta_t
$$

Or more directly:

$$
{}\text{trade only if}
\quad
U_t(w_t^\star) - U_t(w_t^0)
>
k C_t(w_t^\star, w_t^0)
$$

with

$$
k > 1
$$

This creates a real no-trade region rather than just a weak turnover penalty.

---

## 6. Maturity / Liquidity Preference

Add contract preference or penalty terms based on:

$$
{}\text{tenor}, \quad \text{spread}, \quad \text{Vega}, \quad \text{liquidity}
$$

A generic penalty form:

$$
\lambda_p \sum_i p_{i,t} w_{i,t}^2
$$

Here, $p_{i,t}$ should be larger for undesirable contracts, for example:

$$
p_{i,t} = p(\text{wide spread}, \text{bad tenor}, \text{low liquidity}, \text{unstable Vega})
$$

If $p_{i,t}$ is instead defined as a positive preference score, then the sign should be reversed in the objective.

---

## 7. Diagnostic Tests

### 7.1 Post-Optimization Exposure Tracker

Track daily exposures after optimization:

$$
x_{\Gamma,t} = b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w_t
$$

$$
x_{\mathrm{Vega},t} = b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t
$$

$$
x_{\mathrm{Vanna},t} = b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}^\top w_t
$$

Compare optimizer exposure path against manual strategy exposure path.

---

### 7.2 Turnover Statistics

Break turnover down by:

$$
{}\text{tenor}, \quad \text{moneyness}, \quad \text{Vega}, \quad \text{spread}, \quad \text{option type}
$$

Useful statistics:

$$
\sum_i \lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert
$$

$$
\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert
$$

$$
\frac{\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert}{\sum_i \lvert w_{i,t} \rvert}
$$

---

### 7.3 Trade-Level Alpha / Cost Ratio

For each trade, compare predicted factor alpha against cost:

$$
\frac{\pi_t^\top B_t^\top \Delta w_t}{\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert}
$$

If this ratio is small, the optimizer is paying cost without gaining much factor exposure.

---

## 8. Gross Factor PnL vs. Net PnL

Track both:

$$
\mathrm{GrossPnL}_{t+1} = w_t^\top r_{t+1}
$$

and

$$
\mathrm{NetPnL}_{t+1} = \mathrm{GrossPnL}_{t+1} - C_t(w_t, w_t^0)
$$

Also compare:

$$
\mathrm{GrossFactorPnL}
\quad
{}\text{vs.}
\quad
\mathrm{NetPnL}
$$

This separates factor premium from implementation cost.

---

# Part II. Alpha, Cost, Risk, and Trading Path

## 9. Alpha Change Speed

Study how fast the alpha signal changes.

Main question:

$$
{}\text{How do we get the desired exposure with lower cost?}
$$

If alpha rank changes too fast, the optimizer may chase contract-level noise.

Need to compare:

$$
{}\text{alpha signal speed}
\quad
{}\text{vs.}
\quad
{}\text{bid-ask cost}
$$

---

## 10. Risk Term May Produce Turnover

The risk term itself may cause unnecessary turnover.

A generic objective:

$$
\min_{w_t}
\quad
\lambda_{\mathrm{tc}} \sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert w_{i,t} - w_{i,t}^0 \rvert
+
\frac{\gamma}{2} w_t^\top \Sigma_t w_t
-
\mu_t^\top w_t
+
\lambda_p \sum_i p_{i,t} w_{i,t}^2
$$

Subject to:

$$
L_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
\le
b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}^\top w_t
\le
U_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
$$

$$
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}}
$$

plus other position and turnover constraints:

$$
\sum_i \lvert w_{i,t} \rvert \le A_t
$$

$$
\sum_i \lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert \le T_t
$$

$$
\lvert w_{i,t} \rvert \le u_{i,t}
$$

Need to test whether $\Sigma_t$ causes contract switching even when factor exposure barely changes.

---

## 11. Alpha: Factor Exposure vs. Contract Score

Clarify whether alpha should be attached to:

$$
{}\text{factor exposure}
$$

or

$$
{}\text{individual contract score}
$$

Structural factor alpha:

$$
\mu_t^{\mathrm{factor}} = \pi_{\mathrm{Vanna}} b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
$$

Contract-selection alpha:

$$
\mu_t^{\mathrm{selection}} = \eta s_t
$$

Combined form:

$$
\mu_t = \pi_{\mathrm{Vanna}} b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t} + \eta s_t
$$

Need to test whether $s_t$ has net value after spread cost.

---

## 12. Gamma / Vega Constraints

Core exposure constraints:

$$
\lvert b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\Gamma}
$$

$$
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}}
$$

Need to test whether these bands are too tight.

If bands are too tight, optimizer may trade frequently just to remove small exposure drift.

---

## 13. Cross-Sectional Stat Arb vs. Short-Skew

Need to separate two possible interpretations:

$$
{}\text{cross-sectional contract selection}
$$

versus

$$
{}\text{structural short-skew / Vanna exposure}
$$

The current strategy should not be treated as generic cross-sectional stat arb.

The core hypothesis is:

$$
{}\text{positive Vanna / short-skew exposure earns a structural premium}
$$

Contract-level selection is secondary and must justify its cost.

---

## 14. Trade Gating

Use trade gating instead of always re-optimizing.

Two-step logic:

1. Check whether current exposure is acceptable.
2. Trade only if expected utility improvement is large enough.

Exposure check:

$$
\lvert b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w_t^0 \rvert \le \epsilon_{\Gamma}
$$

$$
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t^0 \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}}
$$

$$
b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}^\top w_t^0 > 0
$$

If true, default action:

$$
w_t = w_t^0
$$

Only trade if:

$$
U_t(w_t^\star) - U_t(w_t^0) > k C_t(w_t^\star, w_t^0)
$$

where

$$
k > 1
$$

---

## 15. Null-Space Turnover Diagnosis

Decompose trades into exposure-changing and non-exposure-changing parts:

$$
\Delta w_t = \Delta w_t^{B} + \Delta w_t^{\perp}
$$

Here

$$
B_t^\top \Delta w_t^{B} \neq 0
$$

but

$$
B_t^\top \Delta w_t^{\perp} \approx 0
$$

The second part is null-space turnover.

Track:

$$
\Delta x_t = B_t^\top (w_t - w_t^0)
$$

Compare exposure change against cost:

$$
\frac{\lvert \Delta x_t \rvert}{\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert}
$$

If this ratio is small, the optimizer is paying cost while barely changing factor exposure.

---

# Part III. Dynamic Optimizer Design

## 16. Three-Mode Optimizer

Use three modes:

$$
{}\text{Mode A: Hold}
$$

$$
{}\text{Mode B: Repair}
$$

$$
{}\text{Mode C: MVO Improve}
$$

The optimizer should not always run full MVO.

---

## 17. Feasible Set

Define feasible set:

$$
\mathcal{P}_t =
\left\{
w :
\lvert b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w \rvert \le \epsilon_{\Gamma},
\quad
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}},
\quad
b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}^\top w > 0,
\quad
w \in U_t
\right\}
$$

More stable version:

$$
\mathcal{P}_t =
\left\{
w :
\lvert b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w \rvert \le \epsilon_{\Gamma},
\quad
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}},
\quad
L_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
\le
b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}^\top w
\le
U_{\mathrm{Vanna},t},
\quad
w \in U_t
\right\}
$$

---

## 18. If $\lambda_{\mathrm{tc}} \to \infty$ Still Trades, There Is a Structural Issue

Important test:

$$
\lambda_{\mathrm{tc}} \to \infty
$$

If the optimizer still trades heavily, the issue is not turnover penalty size.

Possible structural cause:

$$
U_t^{\mathrm{solve}}
\neq
U_t^{\mathrm{candidate}}
\cup
\operatorname{supp}(w_t^0)
$$

Better solve universe:

$$
U_t^{\mathrm{solve}} =
U_t^{\mathrm{candidate}}
\cup
\operatorname{supp}(w_t^0)
$$

If old holdings are not in the new universe, the optimizer cannot hold old contracts, so it is forced to trade.

Need to investigate universe construction carefully.

---

## 19. Factor Premium vs. Contract Selection

Separate two sources of return:

$$
{}\text{factor premium}
$$

and

$$
{}\text{contract selection}
$$

Test sequence:

$$
\mu_t = \mu_t^{\mathrm{factor}}
$$

first.

Then add contract score:

$$
\mu_t = \mu_t^{\mathrm{factor}} + \eta \mu_t^{\mathrm{selection}}
$$

Sweep:

$$
\eta \in \{0, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 1.0\}
$$

If $\eta = 0$ works but $\eta > 0$ hurts net PnL, the contract score is causing costly turnover.

---

## 20. Rank-Gaussianization and Rank Stability

If alpha score is rank-gaussianized, check whether rank information persists.

Compute:

$$
\operatorname{corr}(z_t, z_{t-1}^{+})
$$

If rank correlation is low, the score changes too fast for a high-spread option universe.

Use the three-mode test:

$$
\{\text{Hold}, \text{Repair}, \text{Improve by MVO}\}
$$

Define utility:

$$
U_t(w) = \mu_t^\top w - \frac{\gamma}{2} w^\top \Sigma_t w
$$

Accept Improve mode only if:

$$
U_t(w_t^\star) - U_t(w_t^0) > k C_t(w_t^\star, w_t^0)
$$

with

$$
k > 1
$$

---

## 21. Smooth Alpha Signal or Shrink Alpha

Smooth the alpha signal or rank:

$$
\hat z_{i,t} = (1 - \rho)\tilde z_{i,t} + \rho \hat z_{i,t-1}^{+}
$$

Here,

$$
	ilde z_{i,t}
$$

is the raw current signal, and

$$
\hat z_{i,t-1}^{+}
$$

is yesterday’s smoothed signal mapped into today’s universe.

This reduces unnecessary switching caused by noisy daily rank changes.

Alternative shrinkage:

$$
\mu_t^{\mathrm{shrunk}} = \eta \mu_t
$$

with

$$
0 \le \eta \le 1
$$

---

## 22. Alpha-Free Version of the Optimization

Before using alpha, test an alpha-free optimizer.

Objective:

$$
\min_{w_t}
\quad
C_t(w_t, w_t^0)
+
\frac{1}{2} w_t^\top \Sigma_t w_t
+
\lambda_{\mathrm{liq}} \sum_i p_{i,t} w_{i,t}^2
$$

Subject to:

$$
\lvert b_{\Gamma,t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\Gamma}
$$

$$
\lvert b_{\mathrm{Vega},t}^\top w_t \rvert \le \epsilon_{\mathrm{Vega}}
$$

$$
L_t \le z_t^\top w_t \le U_t
$$

Here $z_t$ can represent the target structural exposure, for example Vanna:

$$
z_t = b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
$$

This test answers:

$$
{}\text{Can the optimizer maintain the desired exposure cheaply even without alpha?}
$$

If alpha-free optimization already trades too much, the problem is likely universe construction, constraints, or cost modeling.

---

# Suggested Research Flow

## Stage 1. Verify the Baseline

Re-run the manual strategy under the same cost model:

$$
\mathrm{GrossPnL}, \quad \mathrm{SpreadCost}, \quad \mathrm{NetPnL}
$$

This checks whether the backtest engine and cost accounting are consistent.

---

## Stage 2. Alpha-Free Hold / Repair Test

Run only:

$$
{}\text{Hold}
\quad
{}\text{or}
\quad
{}\text{minimum-cost Repair}
$$

No MVO improve, no contract alpha.

Goal:

$$
{}\text{Can the optimizer maintain Gamma/Vega-neutral positive-Vanna exposure cheaply?}
$$

---

## Stage 3. Add Structural Vanna Alpha

Use:

$$
\mu_t = \pi_{\mathrm{Vanna}} b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t}
$$

No contract score yet.

Goal:

$$
{}\text{Test whether structural Vanna premium is tradable after cost.}
$$

---

## Stage 4. Add Trade Gating

Only trade if:

$$
U_t(w_t^\star) - U_t(w_t^0) > k C_t(w_t^\star, w_t^0)
$$

This separates real improvement from optimizer churn.

---

## Stage 5. Add Contract Score

Use:

$$
\mu_t = \pi_{\mathrm{Vanna}} b_{\mathrm{Vanna},t} + \eta s_t
$$

Sweep:

$$
\eta \in \{0, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 1.0\}
$$

Goal:

$$
{}\text{Check whether contract-level selection survives bid-ask cost.}
$$

---

## Stage 6. Universe and Null-Space Diagnostics

Use solve universe:

$$
U_t^{\mathrm{solve}} =
U_t^{\mathrm{candidate}}
\cup
\operatorname{supp}(w_t^0)
$$

Track:

$$
\Delta x_t = B_t^\top \Delta w_t
$$

Track null-space cost:

$$
\frac{\lvert \Delta x_t \rvert}{\sum_i c_{i,t}\lvert \Delta w_{i,t} \rvert}
$$

Low value means:

$$
{}\text{high cost, little exposure change}
$$

That is the key sign of null-space turnover.
